1. Artificial Intelligence (AI)
Definition

Artificial Intelligence (AI) is the field of making computers perform tasks that normally require human intelligence.

These tasks include:

Thinking
Learning
Solving problems
Understanding language
Making decisions

AI is the big umbrella that contains many technologies.

Real-Life Example

Google Maps finds the fastest route by analyzing traffic.

It behaves intelligently, so it is considered AI.

Easy Analogy

Imagine AI as a school.

The school teaches many subjects.

Similarly, AI contains many branches like ML, DL, NLP, Robotics, and Computer Vision.

2. Machine Learning (ML)
Definition

Machine Learning is a subset of AI where computers learn patterns from data instead of following only fixed rules.

Instead of programming every decision, we give the computer examples, and it learns from them.

Example

Netflix recommends movies based on your viewing history.

It learns your preferences from data.

Why ML?

Without ML:

If age > 18
    Adult
Else
    Child

Works only for simple problems.

For complex problems like predicting customer churn or recommending products, writing rules becomes impossible.

ML learns these patterns automatically.

3. Deep Learning (DL)
Definition

Deep Learning is a subset of Machine Learning that uses neural networks with many layers to learn complex patterns.

It can automatically learn features from images, speech, and text.

Example

Face Unlock on your phone.

The phone recognizes your face without manually defining every facial feature.

Why DL?

Traditional ML often needs humans to decide which features are important.

Deep Learning learns those features automatically from large datasets.

4. Natural Language Processing (NLP)
Definition

NLP is the branch of AI that helps computers understand, process, and generate human language.

Example

Gmail Spam Detection

The system reads the email text and predicts whether it is spam.

Before LLMs

Older NLP systems used:

Grammar rules
Dictionaries
Statistical methods

They worked well for specific tasks but struggled with open-ended conversations.

5. Large Language Model (LLM)
Definition

An LLM is a Deep Learning model trained on massive amounts of text to predict the next token.

It understands context and generates human-like text.

Example

ChatGPT

You ask:

"Explain Python."

It predicts one token at a time until it forms a complete answer.

Why LLMs?

Traditional NLP could classify or extract information.

LLMs can:

Answer questions
Write code
Translate languages
Summarize documents
Generate emails
6. Generative AI (GenAI)
Definition

Generative AI creates new content such as text, images, code, music, audio, and videos.

LLMs are one type of Generative AI focused on text.

Example

Prompt:

"Write a Python program to calculate factorial."

ChatGPT generates brand-new code.

Or:

Prompt:

"Create an image of a robot coding in a coffee shop."

An image generation model creates a new image.












